ce:section.ce:para:
The feasibility of BNP1 for in vivo fluorescent imaging was evaluated on H22 tumor-bearing KM mice. Before imaging, the back and abdomen areas of mice were shaved to avoid autofluorescence [32, 42–45]. The mice were injected through the tail vein with BNP1 (2 μg/mL, 0.3 mL) and then subjected to fluorescence imaging with the Maestro 500 FL in vivo optical imaging system. As shown in Fig. 5
                        a, at the initial injection time (1 min), compared to other organs, the fluorescence signal in the liver was the strongest, indicating that BNP1 accumulates in the liver. However, the fluorescence intensity at the tumor site enhanced significantly over time and reached to the highest level on the 4th day. Subsequently, the signal in tumor slowly faded with the metabolism of BNP1 in mouse. Finally, the fluorescence signal of the tumor site almost disappeared on the 14th day. It is worth mentioning that BNP1 can target the tumor site and accumulate in tumor even at 10 days post injection. As a control, in vivo bioimaging of BODIPY and ANP4 was conducted in a similar way. As shown in Fig. 5a, fluorescence intensity in tumor is very faint for BODIPY. Quantification of the fluorescence intensity of tumor sites in mice administered with BNP1 and BODIPY is shown in Fig. 5b, indicating that BNP1 has a much higher in vivo imaging ability than BODIPY. In addition, the ex vivo fluorescent imaging of major organs (heart, liver, spleen, lung, and kidneys) and the tumor was carried out to quantify the biodistribution of BNP1 (Fig. 6
                        ). The fluorescence in the liver was brightest at 1 min; however, the signal was very weak on the 4th day. In contrast, the signal in the tumor reached the highest on the 4th day and remained intense on the 14th day. These results are in complete agreement with in vivo imaging. BNP1 can effectively accumulate in tumor tissues in the long term at a very low BODIPY loading, which endows it with great potential applications in fluorescence imaging. Because free BODIPY has very poor water solubility, after intravenous injection of BODIPY in PBS containing 2% Tween 80, BODIPY forms large aggregates in physiological media, which causes fluorescence quenching and different biodistribution with BNP1.
